@endnode

@node req "System Requirements"


    @{b}Requirements@{ub}


    o  Amiga OS 3.5 or greater

    o  Popupmenu.libary, included in the archive; get the recent and
       processor optimized version at
       http://www.boing.nu/pm/index.html


    Recommended:

    o  Amiga OS 3.9 with BoingBag2
    o  xadmaster.library (please notice: that's shareware!)
    o  The utilities "Lha" and "Zip", and many other tools
       to be used in your actions for display, edit and more.
    o  A high resolution like 1024 x 768
    o  Enough speed, like a 68060 or more
@endnode

@node cap "Configuration"


    @{b}Configuration@{ub}


    All the configuration is done with ClassActionPrefs.
    You don't have to edit tooltypes or config files, just
    start ClassActionPrefs - for example from the ClassAction
    menu - and change the settings.

    You can choose between three parts:

    o @{" Options   " link options }

      Some global properties of the ClassAction window, the
      way ClassAction works and how it looks.

    o @{" Commands  " link commands}

      The icons on the top and bottom of the window and the
      key commands.

    o @{" Classes   " link classes }

      The classes and actions - the most important part.

    o @{" Path list " link paths }

      The shortcuts to your often used directories.


    The menu has items known from standard preference programs:

    @{b}Project:@{ub}

    o Open...   - open a definition file from somewhere on disk
    o SaveAs... - save a definition file to a file
    o Help      - show this manual


    @{b}Edit:@{ub}

    o Reset to defaults - is not yet implemented
    o Last Saved        - loads the settings you have last saved
                          in ClassActionPrefs
    o Restore           - resets the settings to the state as you
                          started ClassActionPrefs



    When you have done all changes, use @{b}Save@{ub} to make this the
    standard for ClassAction, or @{b}Use@{ub} to try it only this
    session (until you reboot). @{b}Cancel@{ub} or the close button
    will discard your changes.

@endnode

@node options "Options"


    @{b}Options@{ub}


    Some ClassAction features are configurable. To change them, just
    start ClassActionPrefs, adjust the options and use "Save" or "Use".

    Remark: If you have changed the options while ClassAction is
    running, ClassAction will restart to use the new settings.

    Some of the options can also be modified inside ClassAction.
    They can be found in the @{" Settings menu " link menu}.

    This is the list of available options. Some are switches and get a
    hook if you click on them, some have values that can be modified
    by a click. Please don't click on the hook square, click on the
    entry itself.


    @{b}General:@{ub}

    Start as icon

        If you choose this option, ClassAction will start as an AppIcon.
        Use it for example if you start ClassAction from WBStartup.

    Iconify by close gadget

        MUI applications can be iconified when you click on the close
        gadget of the window. As ClassAction was such an application
        and doesn't want you to change your habits ;) you can activate
        this behaviour.

    Menu is pulldown menu

        If you switch this on, the ClassAction main menu will appear as
        pulldown menu on the top of the window. Else it will appear as
        popupmenu on the current mouse position.
        (This behaviour depends on your popupmenu.library settings.)

    Menu font

        The popup menus use the standard window font by default.
        If you want another font or another size, just choose it here.

    Cli size

        It is the size of the CLI output window, if a command of type
        CLI is executed.

        The syntax is : DEVICE:TopX/TopY/Width/Height/Title

        Thus you can select another device than CON: for the CLI's
        or define a new window position and dimension.

        WARNING :

        If you set this to a weird value, ClassAction will not
        launch CLI.
        DON'T modify it unless you know what you are doing.

        ** NEVER ** add device commands such AUTO, CLOSE, WAIT
        to this string, ClassAction will do it for you.

        ** NEVER ** put spaces into the title.

        Default Value is :
                 CON:0/0/640/100/ClassAction_Output_Window

    Public screen

        Perhaps you use another screen and want to start ClassAction
        on this public screen. If you know its name, just enter it
        here and ClassAction and ClassActionPrefs will use this
        screen instead of the workbench. If no name or "Workbench"
        is entered, the Workbench will bes used as usual.

   Popup key
   Hide key

        These are the commodity shortcuts for ClassAction. The popup
        key does the same as a double click on the ClassAction
        Appicon: it opens the window. If it is open it will be moved
        to the front and be activated.
        The hide key hides the window, it iconifies it like the menu
        item or the iconify button.
        You can enter a sequence of qualifiers and keys known from
        other commonities - use CTRL, ALT, SHIFT, LAMIGA, RAMIGA for
        the qualifiers and then the key, e.g. SHIFT F10 or
        CTRL LAMIGA T.
        The default keys are CTRL ALT F1 and CTRL ALT F2.


    @{b}Copy and delete:@{ub}


    Buffer size in KB

        Enter the space that ClassAction shall use for copying. That
        means: if you enter e.g. 100, ClassAction will copy all files
        by reading and writing blocks of 100 kb.

    Count files before copy

        The progress bar can only display the correct state if you
        switch this option on. Then ClassAction will count the
        selected files and all files in subdirectories, and display
        the progress as the relation copied files/selected files.

    Check space before copying

        To check if the selected files fit on the destination volume
        before ClassAction starts copying, switch this on.

    Confirm replace

        If you click on 'copy' or a related button, there exists a
        probability that an old file is replaced by the new one. If
        "Confirm replace" is set, you will be asked in such a case
        whether you do really want to delete the old file.

   Show version when copying

        If ClassAction detects that it must override a file to copy
        another to the same place, it displays a requester if the
        option "Confirm replace" isn't switched off. If you want to
        see also the version of both files, you can also switch on
        this option.

   Replace older versions when copying

        Normally ClassAction copies all files or asks you if you want
        to replace existing files. Activate this hook if you want
        ClassAction to decide itself to replace files that have an
        older version than the file to copy. This doens't affect
        files which don't contain a version identifier.

   Delete protected files

        Amiga OS checks if the file to be deleted is protected
        against deletion. So ClassAction detects an error when trying
        such an action. ClassAction will then remove the protection
        and try again to delete the file.
        With this option this is done automatically, else you are
        asked if you really want to delete the file. @{b}So be careful
        when using this option as you must know if the deletion of
        this file doesn't affect your system and all of the installed
        programs !!@{ub}


    @{b}Window:@{ub}


    Left Edge, Top Edge

        Specify the distance of the ClassAction window from the left
        and top margin of the screen.
        If they are both -1, the window is centred on the screen.

    Width, Height

        Give the width and height of the window.
        If not given, the size is adjusted to the window gadgets.

    AppIcon left edge, AppIcon top edge

        Usually the AppIcon will be put on the workbench according
        to the position of the program icon. If this is not your
        preferred place, enter these values. A value of -1 won't
        change the position.

    Background

        Specify any background pattern for the ClassAction window.
        To see the changes, iconify ClassAction and open it again.
        There are some examples in the subdir "patterns".
        This will overwrite the Reaction settings.


    @{b}Buttons:@{ub}

    Parent

        Show and use the parent gadget left to the path in source and
        destination listers.

    Refresh

        Show and use the refresh button left to the path in source and
        destination listers.


    @{b}Listers:@{ub}

    Arrange vertically

        Normally you should be content with one lister on the left
        and the other on the right side. If you want to have one on
        the top and the other below it, just activate this switch.

    Show images

        Images are really nice, but if you don't have much space or
        you think the icons are ugly :( turn this option off.
        You should then turn on "Highlight directories".

    Use small images

        Check this option to have smaller images left to the files/dirs.

    Show devices

        In most cases you are content with volumes and assigns - but
        if you want to see also the devices select this option.
        (This can be interesting if you have installed an env:
        handler etc.)
        Remember that you can always enter the path directly into
        the path gadget without having to list the device.

    Highlight directories

        Turn this on to show directories and volumes in white colour.
        Else they are written black like other entries.

    Show drawers first

        Use this option to adjust the way the file listers are sorted.
        If active, directories are positioned at the top of the list.

    Show date as text

        If this is activated, some dates are replaced by a text, like
        "Today","Monday" etc.

    Display also time

        ClassAction shows the date of the last changes for each file,
        and aditionally the time if you activate this switch.

    Update on changes

        ClassAction can detect a disk change. Specify this option if
        you want that ClassAction rereads the volume list if this
        happens.

    Cached paths

        ClassAction can store the contents of a directory in a buffer
        to fasten the display. Here you can specify how many paths
        shall be stored. Think of the memory ClassAction will need
        for this purpose. The buffering means also that changed
        directories must be refreshed if this is not done
        automatically by a ClassAction command. Simply click on the
        refresh button to read the current contents.

    Path buttons

        You can use path buttons to switch between directories fast
        and easy. Here you can set the number of buttons ("tabs").
        Set it to 1 to have only one tab that is hidden.

    Path buttons transparent

        Set this if you don't want to see filled buttons for the
        paths.

    Source start path

        This is the directory that is listed in the source lister
        when ClassAction starts.

    Destination start path

        The same as "Source start path" for the destination.

    Lister font

        This is the font you will see in the lister both for the title
        and for the entries.


    @{b}Icons:@{ub}

    Display icons

        If you select this option, .info files will be
        shown in the listers.

    Create icons

        The 'makedir' button creates a new directory and asks if you
        also want to create an icon for this directory.
        This switch is only the standard decision for each new
        directory.

    Copy icons

        With this option activated, the 'copy' and related buttons
        will copy also the icon if you copy a file. This is useful if
        "Display icons" is not set.

    Delete icons

        If you delete a file, ClassAction looks for a related icon
        and deletes it as well if this option is checked. Deselect it
        to keep the icon.


    @{b}Supported archives@{ub}

    This is a list of standard archives that can be supported by
    ClassAction if xadmaster.library is installed. xadmaster.library
    supports many archive types, but ClassAction will only use types
    that are tested. Write me an email if you want to see another
    type here.
    This list means: if you activate an archive type, this suffix
    identifies a file as an archive. If you use files like abc.ha
    that are NO archives, you will get problems. So only activate
    the archive types you need.

    ClassAction will copy files only into LHA and ZIP archives with
    the tools lha and zip, if they are installed.


    See also

    @{" Settings menu " link menu}
@endnode


@node commands "Commands"


    @{b}Commands@{ub}


    You can configure the icons on the top and on the bottom, and you can
    define key commands that do not have an icon.

    To get an overview, just start ClassActionPrefs and look at the
    predefined icons.


    You can add a command with the button "Add" on the left bottom.
    Then move it with the arrows to the place you want to have it.

    @{b}Name and help@{ub}

    Specify a short name. This is only used in ClassActionPrefs and has no
    meaning for ClassAction. It is the text you will see in the left lister.

    Specify a help text that is shown in ClassAction, if
    "Show help" is turned on.

    @{b}Command@{ub}

    The most important part is the command itself:

    first decide, if you want to start something by Cli (CLI), by Cli
    without a window (No CLI), by Workbench (WB), as ARexx script (ARexx)
    or as @{" internal command " link internalcom} (Internal), see @{" modes " link modes}.
    If you configure the icon bars, you may want to have some space between
    icons, so create a command and use SPACE as type. With a SPACE before
    and after the icons, you can center them in the toolbar.

    Now choose the command. You have several possibilities:

    o Enter the command in the string gadget.
    o Click on the button on the right and then search for the program
      you want to insert.
    o If you want to use an internal command, click on "Internal commands"
      and select the one you want.

    Additionally you can use some internal variables that are replaced by
    the selected file, the shown paths, a string or file requested from the
    user ... See @{" variables " link vars} for a complete description.

    @{b}Icon@{ub}

    If you want to see the command as icon in the ClassAction window, you
    have to specify an icon file. Enter the name of the file that has an
    icon (ClassAction will hide the ending ".info" if you enter it).
    You can have a preview of the icon by clicking on the magnifier button,
    or even of the whole icon bar when you choose the group in the lister
    and then the button.
    The rightmost button will open a Workbench window showing all icons in
    the drawer MRE:icons. You can draw one of them onto the ClassActionPrefs
    window.

    @{b}Key@{ub}

    Finally you can choose also a key for this command. If it is a key
    command, this is the only way you can call it.
    You have two choices: ASCII or RAWKEY.

    ASCII takes a printable character like 'a', 'W' or ':' and is case
    sensitive.
    RAWKEY identifies the number of the pressed key. Thereby you can define
    keys like F1,...,F10 or ESC,DEL,TAB,RETURN ...
    If you don't know the number of the key ;) press "Select RAW key"
    and then the key you want to define. The number will immediately be
    shown.

    Be careful not to overwrite other commands you want to use; HELP key and
    the latin characters ('a'-'z','A'-'Z') are already used by ClassAction,
    but your defined commands will overwrite the internal commands.


    @{b}Remarks@{ub}

    Notice that a command is executed once or more times depending on the
    following:
    o   if you use one of the [a*] or [A*] options or no filevariable at all,
        the command is only executed once;
    o   if you have used a filevariable without the "a" option, the command
        is executed for each selected file.


    See also

    @{" Internal Commands " link internalcom}
    @{" Modes             " link modes}
    @{" Variables         " link vars}

@endnode

@node paths "Paths"


    @{b}Path list@{ub}

    ClassAction wouldn't be user friendly if it didn't offer a possibility to
    define some directories that you often want to see and work on.
    These paths are shown in the path popup menu and in the "Copy to" submenu
    over selected files.

    The defining is very simple: use "Add" to add such a path. You are asked
    for a directory and then for a name that shall be displayed as shortcut in
    ClassAction. Use "Remove" and the arrows to delete an entry or move it up
    and down.

    You can change the name or directory, if you double click on it and enter
    the new value.

    You don't have to add your volumes here as there is a special volume menu
    above the refresh button.

@endnode


@node classes "Classes"


    @{b}Classes@{ub}


    Defining new classes and actions is the heart of the program.
    To do so, you must use ClassActionPrefs program.

    Using ClassActionPrefs should be easy... so let's go !!


    The window is divided into two parts : Classes & Actions.

    First select a class, the associated actions will be displayed
    on the actions part.

    To add a class or delete a class, simply click on the associated
    buttons.


    It's the same concept for the actions...


    @{" 1. What is a Class       " link PrefsWhatIsClass}

    @{" 2. Creating a new Class  " link PrefsCreateClass}

    @{" 3. Defining a new action " link PrefsNewAction}

    @{" 4. The learn function    " link PrefsLearn}


    See also

    @{" Description of classes   " link stdclasses}
@endnode

@node PrefsLearn "Using the learn function"


    @{b}Using the learn function@{ub}


    The learn function is provided to help you defining new classes.

    When you define a new class, you may have to define offsets for it,
    and it may be long and boring to edit files to guess which offsets
    could define this new class.

    This is why the marvellous function learn has been made !

    To use it, just follow this procedure :

    1 : Define your class as normal, fill name and classname.

    2 : Click on the 'learn' button.

    3 : Select with the provided requester as many files you want
        as long as they belong to the class you want to define.
        The more files you select, the better will be the result.
        ClassAction will try to find out the offsets definition.
        (to select multiple files, use the shift key.)

    4 : After analysis, you have a window with found offsets.

    5 : Modify them by hand if needed.

    6 : Click on 'Accept' to use the offsets for your class.
        or on 'Cancel' to cancel.


    WARNING :

    If you want the learn function works you must be sure that :

        * ALL CHOOSEN FILES BELONG TO THE SAME CLASS.

        * ALL CHOOSEN FILES ARE NOT CRUNCHED.
@endnode

@node PrefsWhatIsClass "What is a Class"


    @{b}What is a class?@{ub}


    A class is a familly of files. For example C files can be
    considered as a Class, let's call it C Class.

    With ClassActionPrefs you can define as many classes as you
    want, as long as you explain how to recognize it.

    To explain how to recognize a Class, there are two methods :
    the match name and the file contents.

    Matchname attribute is used to recognize a file regarding
    it's name.
    Offsets attributes are used to recognize a file with it's contents.

    There are some Built-in Classes that you cannot remove, they are
    displayed in white in the Classes ListView and cannot be renamed.

    The first one is called "Open With". It's not a real class but a
    list of actions that will be displayed in the submenu "Open with".
    You can add any action here, but should use commands like
    "sys:utilities/multiview [f]" etc. that represent a program start
    with the file as parameter.

    The second one is called "Unknown Class"
    This Class contains all the files that ClassAction cannot recognize.

    The next one is called "Generic Actions"; it contains actions that
    will be displayed for all classes (at the end of the list).
    Be careful: these actions should really work with ALL file types!!

    Example: if you want to have an action 'CopyToMyDir' for all the
    classes, you can create it for each class you define, but it's
    looooong and boring.
    A better way to do that is to create this action in the
    "Generic Action" class, so 'CopyToMyDir' will be displayed for all
    the classes.

    The generic actions are only visible in the ClassAction Window.
    They will not be displayed when ClassAction is an AppIcon,
    or via Arexx command Load.

    The next class is the "Volume" class. You can add some actions like
    "DiskCopy" or "MakeBackup" just as you like.

    The last one is called "Directory" and holds actions available
    when you select a directory. Remember that actions for the
    listed directory are available through the directory popup menu.

@endnode

@node PrefsCreateClass "Creating a new Class"


    @{b}Creating a new class@{ub}


    Just Click on the 'add' button on the classes part to add a class.

    A class has 3 properties :

        - a name
        - a pattern
        - offsets


    o   The @{b}name@{ub} is simply the class name, it's up to you to choose it.
        WARNING : a class name must be unique.


    o   The @{b}pattern@{ub} is any regular AmigaDos pattern, like :

            #?.c , mod.#? , #?.c|#?.h , #?b[a|c] , #?toto? .......

        (read the AmigaDOS manual for all wildcards)
        WARNING : Don't use wilcard * but use #? instead.

        The pattern is not case sensitive, thus toto.C match with #?.c

        Notice: pattern recognition is always faster than offset recognition.
        Therefore if you have the choice, please use a pattern. Some
        features work correct only for classes with defined pattern because
        the offset recognition would take too much time.

        If you define a class using a pattern, you must be sure that
        the definition is always good.

        Example : if you define the GIF class with the pattern #?.gif
                  all files with .gif will be recognized as GIF files.

                  But are you sure that ALL .gif files are GIFs, or
                  that all your GIFs have the .gif extension ?


    o   If not, you should use @{b}Offsets@{ub}.

        An offset is a place in a file where we should find something
        to recognize it.

        For example, GIF pictures always begin with string 'GIF' at the
        offset 0.

        Notice: offset recognition is always slower than pattern recognition.
        Therefore if you have the choice, please use a pattern.


        There are three syntaxes for defining offsets :


        ===================================================================

        @{b}Syntax #1 :@{ub}   Offset,HexString

            Offset is a DECIMAL number holding the Offset.
            HexString is an HEX string that should be found at that offset.

            Example 1 : 0,4f4a   means that the file must begin with bytes
                                 $4f and $4a at the position 0

            Example 2 : 9,448b3c means that at byte #9, we should find
                                 $44 $8b $3c


        ===================================================================

        @{b}Syntax #2 :@{ub}   Offset,'String'

            Offset is a DECIMAL number holding the Offset.
            String is an ASCII string that should be found at that offset.

            Example 1 : 0,'GIF'   means that the file must begins with
                                  string 'GIF'
            Example 2 : 9,'FuBar' means that at byte #9, we should find
                                  string 'FuBar'


        ===================================================================

        @{b}Syntax #3 :@{ub}   Offset,"String"

            Offset is a DECIMAL number holding the Offset.
            String is an ASCII string that should be found at that offset.

            Note the difference with the previous syntax, here we use "
            to define the string, and in syntax #2 we used '.

            It's the same concept than in Syntax #2 but here, the string
            comparison is NOT CASE SENSITIVE.

            For example : an AmigaGuide file always begin with string :
            @database in lower or upper case.

            If you use method #2 to recognize an amigaguide file, with
            0,'@database', ClassAction will not declare a file beginning
            with @DATABASE as an AmigaGuide file.

            It works if offset is defined with syntax #3 : 0,"@database"


        ===================================================================


        You can define up to 5 Offsets to define a class.
        A file is recognized as a class if all the Offsets match.
        If the file fits more than one class, it will be recognized as
        the class with the most offsets.

        Ex : if the class X is defined like :

        Offset #1 :  0,4a8b6c
        Offset #2 : 58,14

        All the files beginning with 4a8b6c AND having $14 at byte #58
        will be declared as X.

        To define several offets just click on cycle gadget 'Offset #'
        to activate the next offset.


        @{b}Remark@{ub} : The ASCII Class

        There is a built-in Offset command named : ASCII[]

        If you put this Command into Offset #1 (i.e Offset#1=ASCII[]),
        it will match with ASCII Files.
        But ClassAction will try this after everything has failed.
        Thank to this, Amigaguide files (that are ascii) will not be
        recognized as ascii if you have already defined an Amigaguide
        Class.

        Normally you shoudn't use it as I have provided a standard
        Prefs file where the Class 'ASCII' is defined using this
        command. You can also add the ASCII actions to the generic
        class and remove the ASCII class.

@endnode

@node PrefsNewAction "Defining a new action"


    @{b}Defining a new action@{ub}


    Once the class is defined you should define actions for it.
    Each Class can have as many Actions as you want.

    Simply click on the 'Add' button on the action part to add
    an action.

    An action has 5 + x properties:

        - a name
        - a command
        - a run mode
        - a stack size (only if run mode is Cli)
        - a delay (only if run mode is Cli)
        - a number of flags


    o   @{b}Name@{ub} is the name of the action.

    o   @{b}Command@{ub} is an AmigaDOS valid command line or an
        @{" internal command " link internalcom} and can contain parameters.
        YOU SHOULD always use the full path for the executables.

        Example : use C:Copy instead of Copy in exec line.

        You can put in exec lines, @{" Arguments " link vars} and @{" Commands " link comms} built into
        ClassAction.

    o   @{b}Mode@{ub} can be : Cli, WB, No Cli, ARexx or Internal
        (see @{" modes " link modes}).

    o   @{b}Stack size@{ub} is the size of the stack for Cli and No Cli.
        Set it high enough to ensure that the command runs properly.

    o   @{b}Delay@{ub} is only valid for Cli commands; it means the waiting
        time after which the Cli window is closed. Enter 0 to close it
        immediately or -1 to let it stay open.

    o   Flags:
        Set the @{b}Asynchonous@{ub} checkmark to let ClassAction continue
        without waiting for the end of the command.
        Set the @{b}Read source@{ub} or @{b}Read dest@{ub} checkmark if
        ClassAction shall refresh the source or destination lister after the
        execution. This only makes sense without the Asynchronous option.
        Internal commands know when to refresh which lister, so you don't have
        to adjust their flags.
        Set the @{b}CD dest@{ub} checkmark if you want to execute the command
        in the destination directory rather than the source directory. This
        is useful for some cli commands that require this setting.


    @{b}Buttons@{ub}

    o   The Up and Down arrows buttons permit to sort the actions.

    o   'Internal commands' lets you choose one of the built in commands.

    o   'Variables' inserts a built in variable. You get a short hint
        for each one.



    @{b}Remarks@{ub}

    Notice that normally an action is executed for EACH selected file,
    but if you use one of the [a*] or [A*] options (or no filevariable at all),
    it's only executed once.

@endnode

@node modes "Modes"


    @{b}CLI mode@{ub}

    If 'Cli' is choosen, then when selecting the action, the action
    will be launched from a cli and the stack size of the cli will be
    determined by the stack value (default is 4096).

    The run mode Cli will only open a Cli if it's needed (if the
    executable displays something).

    You can define the delay property for CLI:

    If Delay is negative (i.e. Delay = -1), the Cli will wait until
    you close it by hand with the close gadget in the top left
    of the window.

    If Delay is zero (i.e. Delay = 0), the Cli will close itself as
    soon as the task is terminated.

    If Delay is positive (i.e. Delay = n with n>0), the Cli will
    wait n seconds before closing itself, but you can force the Cli
    to close by clicking the close gadget.

    The dimension of the used Cli can be found in the ToolType CLISIZE.


    @{b}WB mode@{ub}

    If 'WB' is choosen, then no cli will be opened, and ClassAction
    will simulate a Workbench launching of the action.
    The first string will be considered an icon, and the next
    arguments are handled as if they would have been dropped on
    the icon.
    Enter '"[F]"' as command, and the filename will be started as if
    you had double-clicked on it.

    WARNING : this mode is only valid with files that have icons,
    and only filenames (full name) should be used as arguments.

    On some system this mode makes problems when used on a directory.


    @{b}NO CLI mode@{ub}

    If 'No Cli' is choosen, no cli will be opened even if the
    program displays something, but the task is still running
    from a CLI.


    @{b}AREXX mode@{ub}

    If 'Arexx' is choosen, it will launch rx with the given exec
    command. Exec command MUST be an arexx script.
    Of course RexxMaster should be Active and Rx in the directory
    Sys:rexxc/ to work.


    @{b}INTERNAL mode@{ub}

    ClassAction has some built in @{" commands " link internalcom} that you can call.
    With them you can transfer files, control the listers or the whole
    program.
    Some commands can be interrupted by the @{b}stop button@{ub} at the bottom
    right. It will become coloured if this is possible.
    Some of the commands can be rebuilt with cli commands, e.g.
    '[SURE:Really delete?]delete [f]' which does nearly the same as 'DELETE',
    but the internal commands have some advantages, like the test for
    replacement or the active progress bar.
    See @{" Internal commands " link internalcom} for a detailed description.


    @{b}SPACE mode@{ub}

    This is no real mode, it only means that this a no command
    but a space between icons. SPACE can not be used for class actions
    and is senseless for key commands.


    See also

    @{" Internal commands " link internalcom}
    @{" Variables         " link vars}
@endnode

@node internalcom


    @{b}Internal commands@{ub}

    ClassAction has some built in commands that you can call.
    Variables are indicated by a small letter. ? allways stands for
    the lister, where S indicates the source, D the destination,
    L the left and R the right lister.

    ABOUT       Show information about the program.
    ADDICON     Add an icon to the selected files. This is chosen
                by the system according to your DefIcons settings.
    ALL         Select all files in the source list
    CLIPCOPY    Copy the selected filenames to the clipboard.
    CLIPPASTE   Copy the files stored in the clipboard to the
                source directory.
    COPY        Copy all selected files to the destination
    COPYAS      Copy all selected files and rename them
    DELETE      Delete all selected files
    DUPLICATE   Make a duplicate of the selected files.
    GETSIZE     Compute and show the size of all selected files
    HELP        Show this manual (standard key: HELP).
    ICONIFY     Iconify the ClassAction window.
    LIST ? dir  List the drawer 'dir' in lister 'n'
                dir: a valid path like sys:tools, can also be
                     omitted for a list of devices
    MAKEDIR ?   Creates a new directory in lister 'n'.
                An icon is created if this option is activated.
    MOVE        Move all selected files to the destination
    MOVEAS      Move all selected files and rename them
    NONE        Deselect all files in the source list
    PARENT ?    Go to the parent directory in lister 'n'
    PATTERN     Select all files that match a pattern. You are asked
                for a pattern according to the standard rules
                (e.g. #? for several unknown characters etc.).
    POPUP       Show the file popup menu.
    PREFS       Open @{" ClassActionPrefs " link cap}.
    QUIT        Leave ClassAction.
    REFRESH ?   Refresh the lister n
    RENAME      Rename the selected files.
    ROOT        Go to the root directory of the selected lister.
    SEARCH      Open the Workbench program Find to look for a
                specific filename or for specific contents.
    SWAP        Swap the contents of source and destination lister
    TOGGLE      Swap the selection state of each file
                selected become unselected and v.v.
    TRASH       Move all selected files to the trashcan if there is one.
                If there is no one on this volume, the files will be
                deleted.
    TYPE        Selects all files that are in the same class as the
                selected one. This can last some seconds as each file
                in the directory must be examined.
    WBINFO      Show WBInfo for all selected files. You must quit
                the requester to continue work.


    @{b}Remarks@{ub}

    o  The behaviour of the transfer commands (COPY,COPYAS,MOVE,MOVEAS)
       can be adjusted in the options ("Copy and delete").

    o  COPY works also with supported @{b}archives@{ub}.

    o  Some commands can be interrupted by the @{b}stop button@{ub}
       at the bottom right. It will become coloured if this
       is possible. Then the not processed files will remain
       selected.

    o  Some of the commands can be rebuilt with cli commands, e.g.
       'SURE[Really delete?]delete "[F]"' which does nearly the same
       as 'DELETE', but the internal commands have some advantages,
       like the test for replacement or the active progress bar.


    See also

    @{" Variables " link vars}
@endnode

@node vars "Variables"


    @{b}Variables@{ub}


    Currently, the following variables are possible :

    Variables for the selected entries:

    [F]    : full path of selected file                 ("full")
    [S]    : full path of selected file without suffix  ("short")
    [B]    : filename  of selected file
    [X]    : filename  of selected file without suffix

    If you want to include the filename in quotes, use the lower letters:

    [f]    : "full path of selected file"
    [s]    : "full path of selected file without suffix"
    [b]    : "filename  of selected file"
    [x]    : "filename  of selected file without suffix"

    And if you want to use ALL files in a single command line (what is
    especially useful for lha etc.), you can add an "a" or "A" for "all":

    [AF]   : full path of all selected files
    [AS]   : full path of all selected files without suffix
    [AB]   : filename  of all selected files
    [AX]   : filename  of all selected files without suffix
    [af]   : "full path of all selected files"
    [as]   : "full path of all selected files without suffix"
    [ab]   : "filename  of all selected files"
    [ax]   : "filename  of all selected files without suffix"

    Variables for the path of the listers:

    [SRC]  : path of the source lister                  ("source")
    [SRCS] : path of the source lister, with trailing '/' if necessary
    [DST]  : path of the destination lister             ("destination")
    [DSTS] : path of the destination lister, with trailing '/' if necessary

    Requester variables:

    [REQD:text] : Requests for a Directory.
    [REQF:text] : Requests for a File.
    [REQT:text] : Requests for a text.
    [SURE:text] : Asks the user to confirm.

    If you want to ask only once for all selected files, choose the O versions
    (it's no NULL, it's the character O for "once"!):

    [OREQD:text] : Requests for a Directory once for all selected files.
    [OREQF:text] : Requests for a File once for all selected files.
    [OREQT:text] : Requests for a text once for all selected files.
    [OSURE:text] : Asks the user to confirm once for all selected files.


    @{b}Examples@{ub}

    Path variables:

    Example : let say you select the file ram:env/sys.prefs

        [F]    = ram:env/sys.prefs
        [S]    = ram:env/sys
        [B]    = sys.prefs
        [X]    = sys
        [SRC]  = ram:env
        [SRCS] = ram:env/

        Use lower letters if you can't ensure that blanks are in the path and
        these would confuse the command:

        [f]    = "ram:env/sys.prefs"
        [s]    = "ram:env/sys"
        ...


    Example : let imagine you've selected the file ram:main.c

    o   The exec line
                 c:copy [f] "[F].bak"
        will be replaced by :
                 c:copy "ram:main.c" "ram:main.c.bak"

    o   The exec line
                 c:copy [f] "[S].bak"
        will be replaced by :
                 c:copy "ram:main.c" "ram:main.bak"

    And, if you have also selected the file main.h:

    o   The exec line
                 c:lha -r a "[SRCS]newarchive" [af]
        will be replaced by :
                 c:copy "ram:newarchive" "ram:main.c" "ram:main.h"

        Remember that SRCS will ensure that the path is correct, if you
        have a subdir, for example it gives "ram:t/" where the filename
        can be appended.


    Requester variables:

        REQ commands popup a requester with the title [text].
        This is useful when you need interactive command lines.

    o   Example:
                c:lha x [f] to [REQD:Choose a Directory to unarchive]

        This will popup a directory requester letting the user to choose
        the target directory, and the selected file [f] will be unarchived
        to the selected directory. If you want to dearchive more than one
        file with this command, you could use the O version:

                c:lha x [f] to [OREQD:Choose a Directory to unarchive]


        [REQF:] asks for a file.

    o   Example:
                c:dir [f] > [REQF:Choose a file]


        [REQT:] asks for a text, it's usefull to asks args for example:

    o           c:cpu [REQT:Enter arguments for CPU]


    SURE Command:

        [SURE:text] command will popup a requester with text [text]
        and with 2 buttons : yes / no.
        If the user choose no, the exec line is aborted.
        If the user choose yes, ClassAction will execute the exec line
        on the RIGHT part of the Sure command.

        Example :
            [SURE:Really delete this file ?] C:delete [f]

        This will popup a requester asking the user to reply yes or no
        to the question "Really delete this file ?".
        If the user replies no, nothing is done; if the user replies yes,
        then C:delete [f] is executed.


    @{b}Remarks@{ub}

    o   Of course you can combine any number of arguments / commands in an exec
        line:

        [SURE:Really rename this file] c:rename [f] [REQF:Give me a new name]

    o   Notice that normally a command is executed for EACH selected file,
        but if you use one of the [a*] or [A*] options (or no filevariable at
        all), it's only executed once.

    o   An "O" and "A" variable in one line makes no sense, as the "A" means
        that the command is only executed once, so the "O" requester can only
        be displayed this single time; so the "O" can be omitted.


    See also

    @{" Modes " link modes}
@endnode

@node stdclasses "Standard file types"


    @{b}Standard file types@{ub}


    Here is a list of standard file types with hints and proposals how to use
    them. They are preconfigured in ClassActionPrefs. Some may not work on your
    system as the program paths may differ, so adjust them to your need. If you
    have additional ideas, know other classes or actions, just send an email to
    the @{" author " link Author}.


    @{b}8SVX Sound@{ub}
    Contents:   Standart Amiga IFF Sound File
    Offset:     0,'FORM'        8,'8SVX'
    Actions:
    Play        multiview [f]           NOCLI
    Play        C:play16 [f]            WB

    @{b}ADF@{ub}
    Contents:   Disk archive.
    Pattern:    #?.adf
    Actions:
    WriteToDisk c:transadf df0: [f] w v         CLI Delay=0

    @{b}AmigaGuide@{ub}
    Contents:   Structured text. Often used for manuals.
    Pattern:    #?.guide
    Actions:
    View        multiview [f]           NOCLI
    Edit        c:ed [f]                NOCLI

    @{b}ASCII@{ub}
    Contents:   Simple text.
    Offset:     ASCII[]
    Actions:
    View        multiview [f]           NOCLI
    Edit        c:ed [f]                NOCLI

    @{b}ASM@{ub}
    Contents:   Assembler source code.
    Pattern:    #?.s|#?.asm|#?.a
    Actions:
    Edit        c:ed [f]                NOCLI

    @{b}BMP@{ub}
    Contents:   Graphics. Often used from Windows.
    Pattern:    #?.bmp
    Actions:
    View        multiview [f]           NOCLI

    @{b}C@{ub}
    Contents:   C sourcecode, incl. header information.
    Pattern:    #?.c|#?.cpp|#?.h
    Actions:
    View        c:multiview [f]         NOCLI
    Edit        c:ed [f]                NOCLI

    @{b}E@{ub}
    Contents:   E sourcecode.
    Pattern:    #?.e
    View        c:multiview [f]         NOCLI
    Edit        c:ed [f]                NOCLI

    @{b}Executable@{ub}
    Contents:   Executable programs.
    Offset:     0,000003f3000000
    Actions:
    Execute             [f]             NOCLI
    Execute in Cli      [f]             CLI Delay=0
    Execute and wait    [f]             CLI Delay=-1
    Start as icon       [f]             WB
    View        c:type HEX [f]          CLI Delay=-1

    @{b}Font@{ub}
    Contents:   Font.
    Offset:     0,0f0000
    Actions:
    View        multiview [f]           NOCLI

    @{b}FWriter Text@{ub}
    Contents:   FinalWriter document
    Offset:     0,'FORM'        8,'SWRTH'
    Actions:
    Edit        Work:FinalWriter_D/FinalWriter [f]    WB

    @{b}GIF@{ub}
    Contents:   Graphics. Often used in the www.
    Pattern:    #?.gif
    Actions:
    View        multiview [f]           NOCLI

    @{b}HTML@{ub}
    Contents:   HTML formatted file.
    Pattern:    #?.htm|#?.html
    Actions:
    View        aweb3:aweb-ii [f] local NOCLI
    Edit        c:ed [f]                NOCLI

    @{b}IFF picture@{ub}
    Contents:   Image in IFF format.
    Offset:     0,'FORM'        8,'ILBM'
    Actions:
    View        multiview [f]           NOCLI
    Edit        ppaint:ppaint [f]       NOCLI

    @{b}JPEG@{ub}
    Contents:   Graphics. Often used in the www.
    Pattern:    #?.jpg|#?jpeg
    Actions:
    View        multiview [f]           NOCLI

    @{b}LHA@{ub}
    Contents:   Archive. Most used Amiga archive format.
    Pattern:    #?.lha
    Actions:
    Extract     lha x [f] "[DST]"       CLI Delay=0 ReadDest
    View        lha v [f]               NOCLI

    @{b}Library@{ub}
    Contents:   Amiga function library.
    Pattern:    #?.library
    Actions:
    Version     c:version [f]           CLI Delay=2

    @{b}LZX@{ub}
    Contents:   Archive, similar to LHA.
    Pattern:    #?.lzx
    Actions:
    Extract     c:lzx x [f] "[DST]"     CLI Delay=0 ReadDest
    View        c:lzx v [f]             CLI Delay=-1

    @{b}PCX@{ub}
    Contents:   Graphics. Often used from Windows.
    Pattern:    #?.pcx
    Actions:
    View        multiview [f]           NOCLI

    @{b}PDF@{ub}
    Contents:   PDF document.
    Pattern:    #?.pdf
    Actions:
    View        work:apdf/apdf [f]      NOCLI

    @{b}PNG@{ub}
    Contents:   Graphics. Often used in the www.
    Pattern:    #?.jpg|#?jpeg
    Actions:
    View        multiview [f]           NOCLI

    @{b}Postscript@{ub}
    Contents:   Documents.
    Pattern:    #?.ps
    Actions:
    View        gs -sDEVICE=amiga [f]   CLI
    Print       gs -sDEVICE=amiga_printer -dNOPAUSE [f] NOCLI

    @{b}Reaction Resource File@{ub}
    Contents:   Reaction resources (objects).
    Pattern:    #?.res
    Actions:
    OpenReactor storm:tools/reactor/reactor             WB

    @{b}Wordworth@{ub}
    Contents:   Documents.
    Offsets:    0,'FORM'        8,'WOWO'
    Actions:
    Edit        work:wordworth/wordworth [f]            WB

    @{b}ZIP@{ub}
    Contents:   Archive. Often used from Windows.
    Pattern:    #?.zip
    Actions:
    Extract     c:unzip [f] -d "[DST]"  CLI Delay=0 ReadDest


    See also

    @{" Defining new classes " link PrefsCreateClass}
@endnode

@node imp "Future Improvements"


    @{b}Future Improvements@{ub}


    Well, there are many proposals, but some need a lot of time, some make
    the program very big or slow, and some are only interesting for a small
    group of users.

    What could be implemented:

    o import possibility for parts of the prefs, especially for single file
      types

    o import function for DOpus/DefIcons file types







    See also

    @{" Contact " link author}
@endnode

